{% block content %}
  <h2>You do not beat it by chasing every lie</h2>
  <p>By the time a lie is debunked, it has already traveled. The two things that actually work are a trusted source of truth that fills the gap first, and a community that can spot the tactic. That is prebunking: knowing the moves in advance so you recognize them when you meet them.</p>

  <h2>Common tactics to watch for</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>A claim built to make you angry or afraid fast, with no source you can check.</li>
    <li>A real local grievance (the settlement, highway deaths, the drug crisis) bent toward blaming a group of people.</li>
    <li>A screenshot, quote, or video with no link, no date, and no way to verify it.</li>
    <li>An account that is new, anonymous, or far from the community, pushing hard on a divisive message.</li>
    <li>Edited footage that makes someone appear to say or agree with something they did not.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to do</h2>
  <p>Pause before you share. Check whether a trusted, named source carries the same claim. Look for the original, with a date and a link. Ask who benefits from you believing it. When something is being pushed at the community, this hub's "what you have heard, and what the record says" entries are here to give the sourced version.</p>

